{"title_page": "Tolo (Manchu)", "text_new": "{{hatnote|This name uses [[Manchu name|Manchu naming customs]]. The family name is [[Aisin Gioro]].}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name =Tolo\n| title =Dudu Jianzhou Left Guard \n| image = \n| succession =[[List of Chieftains of the Jurchens|Chieftain of the Jianzhou Jurchens]]\n| predecessor =title granted\n| successor = \n| reign = 1467 - 1506\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =1506\n| death_place = \n| burial_place = \n| father =[[Cung\u0161an]]\n| mother = \n| spouse = \n| issue =Toyuebeo\n| house =[[Aisin Gioro]]\n| full name = Aisin-Gioro Tolo<br>(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85\u00b7\u59a5\u7f85)\n| posthumous name = \n}}\n{{Chinese|c=\u59a5\u7f85|p=Tu\u01d2lu\u014d}}\n'''Tolo''' ({{manchu|{{ManchuSibeUnicode|\u1868\u1823\u182f\u1823}}|v=tolo}}<ref>Manchu Veritable Records Vol.1</ref>;?\u20131506) The ancestors of the [[Qing Dynasty]].He is the eldest son of [[Cung\u0161an]], [[Nurhaci]]'s grand uncle. His family name is '''Aisin Gioro'''(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85), his name was translated as '''Tole'''(\u812b\u7f85) and '''Tolv'''(\u571f\u8001).In [[Chenghua Emperor|Chenghua]](\u6210\u5316) years, Three Guard of [[Jianzhou Jurchens|Jianzhou]](\u5efa\u5dde) after [[Ming]] army siege, economy is broken.\n\nIn the Ming dynasty, he commanded tongzhi for the Left Guard of Jianzhou. He was the recovery and development of production, against [[N\u00fczhen]](\u5973\u771f) disturb edge, maintain good relationship with the Ming Dynasty, the Ming Dynasty promoted him for Dudu Jianzhou Left Guard. He died in 1506. His son is [[Toyuebeo]].In 1506, he inherited his father's duty and was still in harmony with the Ming Dynasty.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chu Yan of Jurchen]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|House of Odoli||?||1506}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cung\u0161an]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chieftains of the Jurchens|Chieftain of the Jianzhou Jurchens]]|years=1467\u20131506}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sibeoci Fiyangg\u016b]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolo}}\n[[Category:Manchu people]]\n[[Category:1506 deaths]]\n\n\n{{China-bio-stub}}\n{{noble-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|This name uses [[Manchu name|Manchu naming customs]]. The family name is [[Aisin Gioro]].}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name =Tolo\n| title =Dudu Jianzhou Left Guard \n| image = \n| succession =[[List of Chieftains of the Jurchens|Chieftain of the Jianzhou Jurchens]]\n| predecessor =title granted\n| successor = \n| reign = 1467 - 1506\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =1506\n| death_place = \n| burial_place = \n| father =[[Cung\u0161an]]\n| mother = \n| spouse = \n| issue =Toyuebeo\n| house =[[Aisin Gioro]]\n| full name = Aisin-Gioro Tolo<br>(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85\u00b7\u59a5\u7f85)\n| posthumous name = \n}}\n{{Chinese|c=\u59a5\u7f85|p=Tu\u01d2lu\u014d}}\n'''Tolo''' ({{manchu|{{ManchuSibeUnicode|\u1868\u1823\u182f\u1823}}|v=tolo}}<ref>Manchu Veritable Records Vol.1</ref>;?\u20131506) The ancestors of the [[Qing Dynasty]].He is the eldest son of [[Cung\u0161an]], [[Nurhaci]]'s grand uncle. His family name is '''Aisin Gioro'''(\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85),his name was translated as '''Tole'''(\u812b\u7f85) and '''Tolv'''(\u571f\u8001).In [[Chenghua Emperor|Chenghua]](\u6210\u5316) years, Three Guard of [[Jianzhou Jurchens|Jianzhou]](\u5efa\u5dde) after [[Ming]] army siege, economy is broken.\n\nIn the Ming dynasty, he commanded tongzhi for the Left Guard of Jianzhou. He was the recovery and development of production, against [[N\u00fczhen]](\u5973\u771f) disturb edge, maintain good relationship with the Ming Dynasty, the Ming Dynasty promoted him for Dudu Jianzhou Left Guard. He died in 1506. His son is [[Toyuebeo]].In 1506, he inherited his father's duty and was still in harmony with the Ming Dynasty.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chu Yan of Jurchen]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|House of Odoli||?||1506}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cung\u0161an]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chieftains of the Jurchens|Chieftain of the Jianzhou Jurchens]]|years=1467\u20131506}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sibeoci Fiyangg\u016b]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolo}}\n[[Category:Manchu people]]\n[[Category:1506 deaths]]\n\n\n{{China-bio-stub}}\n{{noble-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, replaced: ,h \u2192 , h", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolo_(Manchu)"}
{"title_page": "Norton Rose Fulbright", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=February 2019}}{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}{{COI|date=February 2019}}{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox Law Firm\n| firm_name = Norton Rose Fulbright\n| logo = [[File:Norton Rose Fulbright logo.svg|270px]]\n| num_offices = 50+\n| key_people = Peter Martyr<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Martyr \u2013 Norton Rose Fulbright|url=http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/people/3658/peter-martyr|publisher=nortonrosefulbright.com}}</ref><br /><small>[[Partner (business rank)|Global Chief Executive]]</small><br />Walied Soliman<ref>{{cite web|title=Tricia Hobson \u2013 Norton Rose Fulbright|url=http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/people/42390|publisher=nortonrosefulbright.com}}</ref><br /><small>[[Partner (business rank)|Global Chair]]</small>\n| num_lawyers = 4,000\n| date_founded = 1794<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law-and-business.net/the-future-of-law-is-bright-with-norton-rose-fulbright/|title=The Future of Law is bright with Norton Rose Fulbright|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007102458/http://law-and-business.net/the-future-of-law-is-bright-with-norton-rose-fulbright/|archivedate=7 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| homepage = [http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/ Norton Rose Fulbright]\n|14 = [[Swiss Verein]]|Organization = [[Swiss Verein]]|Revenue=$2.1 billion (2018)|11=$2.1 billion}}\n'''Norton Rose Fulbright''' is an [[Multinational corporation|international]] [[law firm]]. It is the second largest law firm in the United States and one of the ten largest in the world, by both lawyers and revenue. In 2017/18, Norton Rose Fulbright had total revenue of [[US$]]2.1 billion.\n\nIt has more than 4000 lawyers and other legal staff based in Europe, the United States, Canada, Latin America, Asia, Australia, Africa and the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/us/about-us/global-coverage/|title=Norton Rose Fulbright Global coverage|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|language=|via=}}</ref> \n\nThe firm was formed by the merger of UK-based Norton Rose and US-based [[Fulbright & Jaworski]] in June 2013.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-06-04/norton-rose-goodwin-procter-milbank-business-of-law Norton Rose, Goodwin Procter, Milbank: Business of Law, ''Bloomberg'' 3 June 2013]</ref> \nNorton Rose Fulbright US LLP, Norton Rose Fulbright LLP, Norton Rose Fulbright Australia, Norton Rose Fulbright Canada LLP and Norton Rose Fulbright South Africa Inc are separate legal entities, all of which are members of Norton Rose Fulbright Verein.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\n== History ==\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2019}}The origin of Norton Rose dates back to 1794 when the sole practitioner Robert Charsley opened for business. In 1821, Charsley formed a partnership with William Barker, creating Charsley & Barker. Later that century, Phillip Rose (later [[Sir Philip Rose, 1st Baronet|Sir Philip Rose]]) joined the firm, creating Barker & Rose. In the years that followed, a new partnership between Phillip Rose and Henry Elland Norton was formed under the name Barker, Rose & Norton. By the turn of the 20th century, the firm was called Norton, Rose, Norton & Co., and had maintained its position as a powerful force in the City of London for six decades.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn 1960, the firm, by then re-named Norton, Rose & Co., amalgamated with specialist shipping firm Botterell & Roche (founded 1861) to form Norton, Rose, Botterell & Roche. With its expertise in shipping, the firm benefited from the growth of the international shipping market in the early 1960s, and was involved in the nationalization of [[British Steel (1967\u20131999)|British Steel]] and the after-arrangement of its subsidiary companies.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe firm continued to grow, and in 1976 established its first international office in Hong Kong, followed by Bahrain in 1979 and Singapore in 1982. By 1988, the firm had shortened its name and over the next ten years Norton Rose commenced a programme of international expansion, with the establishment of offices across Asia, Europe and the Middle East, taking the firm\u2019s international operations to 22 offices. In 2007, Norton Rose converted to a Limited Liability Partnership.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nWith a vision to become one of the world\u2019s top global legal brands, Norton Rose embarked on the first phase of rapid expansion when it combined with Australian firm Deacons in 2010, adding to the strength and size of the firm across the Asia-Pacific region. In early 2011, Norton Rose Australia announced an association with a firm in Indonesia.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nBy June 2011, Norton Rose had combined with Canadian law firm [[Ogilvy Renault]] and South African firm Deneys Reitz, creating a top 10 global legal practice with 38 offices and 2500 legal staff, totaling more than 5000 people worldwide. The combination was followed by the opening of new offices in Europe and Africa.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn January 2012, a combination with Canadian firm Macleod Dixon made Norton Rose Group one of the largest law firms in Canada.\n\nOn 3 June 2013, Norton Rose combined with Fulbright & Jaworski to become Norton Rose Fulbright, establishing a market leading presence in the United States and a global law firm with 3800 lawyers and legal staff, and a worldwide headcount of more than 7000 people.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn January 2017, Norton Rose Fulbright combined with leading Vancouver firm, Bull Housser.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/history/|title=Our history|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017 Norton Rose Fulbright combined with Chadbourne & Parke, strengthening its market leading presence in the United States and growing the global firm to more than 4000 lawyers.{{fact|date=October 2018}}\n\nIn December 2017, Norton Rose Fulbright combined with leading Australian firm, Henry Davis York.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/ Norton Rose Fulbright]\n* Firm's rankings: <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.chambersandpartners.com/Global/Firms/309-46041/ Chambers and Partners Global]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.legal500.com/books/l500/ Legal 500 UK]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.legal500.com/books/lfe/ Legal 500 EMEA]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.legal500.com/books/as500/ Legal 500 Asia Pacific]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.legal500.com/c/united-states/ Legal 500 United States]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.legal500.com/books/la500/ Legal 500 Latin America]</span>; <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.chambersstudent.co.uk/Law/FirmFeature/309 Chambers and Partners ''Student Guide'']</span>.\n{{Law firms of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Law firms of England]]\n[[Category:Law firms of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Law firms of Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Law firms based in London]]\n[[Category:Law firms established in 1794]]\n[[Category:Foreign law firms with offices in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Foreign law firms with offices in Japan]]\n[[Category:1794 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Law firms of Australia]]\n[[Category:Law firms of Switzerland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=February 2019}}{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}{{COI|date=February 2019}}{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox Law Firm\n| firm_name = Norton Rose Fulbright\n| logo = [[File:Norton Rose Fulbright logo.svg|270px]]\n| num_offices = 50+\n| key_people = Peter Martyr<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Martyr \u2013 Norton Rose Fulbright|url=http://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/people/3658/peter-martyr|publisher=nortonrosefulbright.com}}</ref><br /><small>[[Partner (business rank)|Global Chief Executive]]</small><br />Walied Soliman<ref>{{cite web|titl