er, Tracking\n* John Tanksley - Production Coordination\n* James Tanskley - Assistant Engineer\n* Damon Thomas - Composer\n* The Underdogs - Instrumentation, Producer\n* Ben Watts - Photography\n* Corey Williams - Composer\n* Curtis \"Sauce\" Wilson - Arranger, Composer, Drums, Keyboards, Producer, Programming, Rhythm\n* Dontae Winslow - Horn\n* Kelvin Wooten - Keyboards\n* Yuan - Design\n* Andrew Zaeh - Art Producer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (2007)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=Musiq (Soulchild)|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|1|artist=Musiq (Soulchild)|rowheader=true}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=Musiq|title= Luvanmusiq |award=Gold}}\n{{certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2007)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2007/top-billboard-200-albums|title=Year-End Charts: Billboard 200 Albums - 2007|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|99\n|-\n| US Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2007/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Year-End Charts: R&B/Hip-Hop Albums - 2007|magazine=Billboard|accessdate=December 18, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416115654/http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2007/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|archivedate=April 16, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{MusiqSoulchild}}\n\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Raphael Saadiq]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Underdogs (production team)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Warryn Campbell]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Musiq Soulchild albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Luvanmusiq\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Musiq Soulchild]]\n| cover      = Luvanmusiq.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2007|3|13}}\n| recorded   = 2006\u201307\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[neo soul]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=48|s=57}}\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Carvin & Ivan]] <br />Harold Lilly<br />[[Jake and the Phatman]]<br />Lab Ratz<br />[[Raphael Saadiq]]<br />[[The Underdogs (duo)|The Underdogs]]<br />[[Theron Feemster|Theron \"Neff-U\" Feemster]]<br />Warryn \"[[Baby Dubb]]\" Campbell\n| prev_title = [[Soulstar (album)|Soulstar]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[OnMyRadio]]\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\n'''''Luvanmusiq''''' (Lovin' Musiq) is the fourth release by the [[singer-songwriter]] [[Musiq Soulchild]], the first under his contract with [[Atlantic Records]]. The lead single, \"[[B.U.D.D.Y.]]\", was released to U.S. radio in late November 2006; it reached number two on the R&B chart,<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/chart_display.jsp?f=Hot+R%26B%2FHip-Hop+Songs&pageNumber=Top+1-10&g=Singles Billboard.com - Charts - Singles - Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and number 36 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=musiq (soulchild)|chart=Hot 100}} Billboard Singles Charts - Billboard Top 100 Songs - Billboard Top 100 Singles<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Following its release, it entered the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at number 1, with 149,774 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1053680/musiq-lloyd-usher-six-big-debuts-onto-album-chart|title=Musiq, Lloyd Usher Six Big Debuts Onto Album Chart|last=Hasty|first=Katie|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=March 21, 2007|accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref> During the same week, the second single, \"[[Teachme]]\", entered the U.S. [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart at number 54, and rose to number five in its thirteenth week. \"Teachme\" also entered the Hot 100 at number 92 on the issue date, May 26, 2007.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/chart_display.jsp?f=Hot+R%26B%2FHip-Hop+Songs&pageNumber=Top+11-50&g=Singles Billboard.com - Charts - Singles - Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> By July 11, 2007, the album had sold 789,377 copies in the U.S.{{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nThe third single from the album was \"Makeyouhappy\", first said in an entry on Soulchild's MySpace blog.<ref>[http://profile.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=user.viewprofile&friendID=28094725 MySpace.com - Musiq Soulchild - Philadelphia, PENNSYLVANIA - Soul - www.myspace.com/musiqsoulchild<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826080153/http://profile.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=user.viewprofile&friendID=28094725 |date=August 26, 2007 }}</ref> The song entered the Hot R&B/Hip-hop Songs chart, peaking at number 61. The album was nominated for [[Best R&B Album]] at the [[50th Grammy Awards]].\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Dotdash|About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://randb.about.com/od/reviews/fr/LovanMusiq.htm|title=Review: Musiq Soulchild - \"Luvanmusiq\"|last=Nero|first=Mark Edward|website=[[Dotdash|About.com]]|accessdate=July 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070326164908/http://randb.about.com/od/reviews/fr/LovanMusiq.htm|archivedate=March 26, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/luvanmusiq-mw0000477682|title=Luvanmusiq - Musiq Soulchild|last=Kellman|first=Andy|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = DJBooth\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"DJB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/musiq-soulchild-luvanmusiq|title=Musiq Soulchild - Luvanmusiq|last=Slavik|first=Nathan|website=DJBooth|date=March 26, 2007|accessdate=July 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420123150/https://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/musiq-soulchild-luvanmusiq|archivedate=April 20, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20016444,00.html|title=Luvanmusiq|last=Endelman|first=Michael|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=March 30, 2007|accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Metromix]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/natent-music-cdreview-musiq-s,0,2764582.story Metromix review]{{Dead link|date=January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n''Luvanmusiq'' received positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. [[AllMusic]] editor Andy Kellman gave note of the record's short running time allowing equal attention for each track and the overall throwback aesthetic being the same as Musiq's previous efforts and not containing \"insincere trend-hopping or ill-fitting collaborations with hot MCs.\" He concluded that \"[T]hey're neither raunchy nor drab, and they're nearly a lost art form in 2007.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> DJBooth's Nathan Slavik gave praise to the musicianship feeling mature throughout the record's track list of slow jams and crowd pleasers, despite the former's combination of lush minimalism and sincere lyricism coming across as \"background music.\" He concluded that, \"If Musiq\u2019s sole intention for this album was to remind us he\u2019s alive, mission accomplished. ''Luvanmusiq'' has several solid tracks, and a couple excellent ones, but as a whole it falls just short of excellent.\"<ref name=\"DJB\"/> Mark Edward Nero from [[About.com]] gave a mixed review of the album, commending Musiq for remaining consistent in terms of his \"soft, deliberate vocal style\" and penchant for romantic ballads but felt that it comes across as though he's shown \"little creative growth as a singer.\" He highlighted the tracks \"Betterman\", \"Makeyouhappy\" and \"Ridiculous\" for having enough content to stand alongside the first single \"B.U.D.D.Y.\" and showcasing Musiq's continued talent as \"one of the better R&B songwriters in the business today\", concluding that \"Although ''Luvanmusiq'' rates pretty low in the excitement and thrills departments, if you take the time to listen to it repeatedly, it's an album whose subtle romantic charm grows on you.\"<ref name=\"About\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = [[B.U.D.D.Y.]]\n| writer1         = T. Johnson, C. Haggins, C. Church, R. Stivalet, K. Nix\n| extra1          = Lab Ratz\n| length1         = 3:45\n| title2          = Ms.Philadelphia\n| writer2         = J. Johnson, [[Ne-Yo|S. Smith]], S. Ridge II, C. Wilson\n| extra2          = [[Somethin' for the People|Curtis \"Sauce\" Wilson]], Musiq Soulchild\n| length2         = 3:56\n| title3          = [[Teachme]]\n| writer3         = C. Haggins, [[Latif (singer/songwriter)|C. Williams]], I. Barias, J. Smith\n| extra3          = Carvin & Ivan\n| length3         = 4:22\n| title4          = Better Man\n| writer4         = T. Johnson, R. Saadiq, R. Ozuna, K. Wooten\n| extra4          = [[Raphael Saadiq]], Jake and The Phatman\n| length4         = 4:39\n| title5          = Thequestions\n| writer5         = T. Johnson, H. Lilly\n| extra5          = Musiq Soulchild, [[Theron Feemster]]\n| length5         = 3:11\n| title6          = Today\n| writer6         = T. Johnson