{"title_page": "Kidderminster Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Kidderminster Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image = Kidderminster Hospital - DSCF0981.JPG\n| Caption = Kidderminster Hospital\n| map_type = Worcestershire\n| map_caption = Shown in Worcestershire\n| latitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| longitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| Location = [[Kidderminster]]\n| Region = [[Worcestershire]]\n| State = \n| Country = England\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.3860|N|2.2611|W|display=inline, title}}\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type = District General\n| Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency = No\n| Affiliation = \n| Beds = \n| Founded = 1884\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| Website = {{URL|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Kidderminster Hospital''' is an acute general hospital in [[Kidderminster]] in [[Worcestershire]], England. It is managed by the [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Kidderminster Union Workhouse Infirmary which was completed about 1884.<ref name=workhouses>{{cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Kidderminster/|title=Kidderminster|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> The hospital joined the [[National Health Service]] as Kidderminster Infirmary and Children's Hospital in 1948.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=2657|title=Kidderminster Minor Injuries Unit, Bewdley Road, Kidderminster|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> It became Kidderminster and District General Hospital in 1974 and Kidderminster General Hospital in 2000.<ref name=na/>\n\nStanding for Parliament as an [[Independent Community and Health Concern|Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern]] candidate at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], [[Richard Taylor (British politician)|Richard Taylor]] campaigned largely on a single issue, that of restoring the accident & emergency department of Kidderminster Hospital, which had been closed the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8655533.stm |title=Wyre Forest candidates back return of Kidderminster A&E|publisher=BBC News |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> A new treatment centre was opened by the [[Birgitte, Duchess of Gloucester|Duchess of Gloucester]] on the site in April 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcsacute.nhs.uk/patient-information-and-leaflets/worcestershire-way/2147-worcestershire-way-july-2017-1/file|title=Celebrating 70 years of the NHS|page=4|date=1 July 2018|publisher=Worcestershire Way|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official site|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Worcestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        =Kidderminster Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image       = Kidderminster Hospital - DSCF0981.JPG\n| Caption     = Kidderminster Hospital\n| map_type    = Worcestershire\n| map_caption = Shown in Worcestershire\n| latitude    = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| longitude   = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = [[Kidderminster]]\n| Region      = [[Worcestershire]]\n| State       = \n| Country     = England\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.3860|N|2.2611|W|display=inline, title}}\n| HealthCare  = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type        = District General\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation = \n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = 1884\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = {{URL|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}} \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Kidderminster Hospital''' is an acute general hospital in [[Kidderminster]] in [[Worcestershire]], England. It is managed by the [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Kidderminster Union Workhouse Infirmary which was completed about 1884.<ref name=workhouses>{{cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Kidderminster/|title=Kidderminster|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> The hospital joined the [[National Health Service]] as Kidderminster Infirmary and Children's Hospital in 1948.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=2657|title=Kidderminster Minor Injuries Unit, Bewdley Road, Kidderminster|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> It became Kidderminster and District General Hospital in 1974 and Kidderminster General Hospital in 2000.<ref name=na/>\n\nStanding for Parliament as an [[Independent Community and Health Concern|Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern]] candidate at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], [[Richard Taylor (British politician)|Richard Taylor]] campaigned largely on a single issue, that of restoring the accident & emergency department of Kidderminster Hospital, which had been closed the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8655533.stm |title=Wyre Forest candidates back return of Kidderminster A&E|publisher=BBC News |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> A new treatment centre was opened by the [[Birgitte, Duchess of Gloucester|Duchess of Gloucester]] on the site in April 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcsacute.nhs.uk/patient-information-and-leaflets/worcestershire-way/2147-worcestershire-way-july-2017-1/file|title=Celebrating 70 years of the NHS|page=4|date=1 July 2018|publisher=Worcestershire Way|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official site|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Worcestershire]]\n", "name_user": "KJD 0115gbr", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidderminster_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "George Burdi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = George Burdi\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| alias               = George Eric Hawthorne\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place         = Canada\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Goth metal]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1988\u20132007, 2017\u2013present\n| associated_acts     = [[RAHOWA (band)|RaHoWa]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''George Burdi''', also known as '''George Eric Hawthorne''' (born 1970), is a Canadian musician and [[white supremacist]] who became known for his role in [[white nationalist]] organizations. He led the Canadian branch of the [[World Church of the Creator]], which formed an alliance with the now-defunct white nationalist organization [[Heritage Front]]. In addition, Burdi performed with the white power band [[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]].<ref name=\"Dyck2016\">{{cite book|author=Kirsten Dyck|title=Reichsrock: The International Web of White-Power and Neo-Nazi Hate Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sREVDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA113|date=3 October 2016|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-7473-8|pages=113\u2013}}</ref>\n\nBurdi was convicted of [[assault causing bodily harm]], and was sentenced to one year in prison. Upon his release from prison, Burdi claimed to have renounced racism, but years later revealed that he actually was and still is a racist.\n\n== Early life ==\nBurdi was born in 1970 to an Italian immigrant father and a Ukrainian mother.\n\n==Activism==\nBurdi came into contact with the white nationalist movement through the father of his then German girlfriend. He became an active White nationalist at the age of 18, and by the age of 21, was the leader of the Canadian branch of the World Church of the Creator, which at its peak had fewer than 20 members.<ref>[http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=179 SPLCenter.org: Present at the Creation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> During this period, he wrote a number of articles for the Church of the Creator newspaper, ''Racial Loyalty'', using the name \"Rev. Eric Hawthorne\" (including the January 1992 cover story, \"Enter the Racial Holy War\"). He has been credited with helping to secure the survival of [[Creativity (religion)|Creativity]] after the death, in 1993, of its founder [[Ben Klassen]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Michael | first1 = George | title = The Church of the Creator Part I: Ben Klassen and the Critique of Christianity | journal = Religion Compass | volume = 4 | pages = 518 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1111/j.1749-8171.2010.00234.x}}</ref>\n\n=== RaHoWa ===\nUsing the pseudonym \"Reverend George Eric Hawthorne\", Burdi formed the racist band [[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]] in 1989. The band's name was derived from the phrase [[Racial Holy War]].<ref name=\"Dyck2016\" /> RaHoWa was one of the largest hate-rock bands throughout the 1990s.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} Burdi was also the founding president of [[Resistance Records]], which was the distributor for his band, and other white nationalist bands. The company also operated a web site, and published a magazine, ''Resistance'', which covered the white nationalist music scene.\n\nIn 2017, Burdi returned to performing with RaHoWa; [[Appalachian State University]] political science professor Nancy S. Love, author of ''Trendy Fascism'', remarked, during a 2018 interview with ''The Financial Times'', that, after having been \"silent for almost 20 years but in 2017 resurfaced, emboldened by the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump presidency]] and also the turn to the right in Europe\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter-Tilney |first1=Ludovic |title=The re-emergence of white supremacist pop |url=https://www.ft.com/content/68033ace-9732-11e8-b747-fb1e803ee64e |accessdate=9 November 2019 |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd. |date=17 August 2018 |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n=== Reckzin incident ===\nIn [[Ottawa]], on May 29, 1993, after a RaHoWa concert which was picketed by [[Anti-Racist Action]] protesters, Burdi and the leader of the White nationalist Heritage Front, [[Wolfgang Droege]], led their supporters on a march to [[Parliament Hill]], chanting \"[[Nazi salute|sieg heil]]\", making racist remarks, and giving the [[Hitler salute]]. At Parliament Hill, the two addressed their followers.\n\nBurdi then led the group to the Chateau Laurier, where he led a charge across the street to confront protesters. During the charge, Alicia Reckzin  was struck on the head while running from Burdi's supporters. When she fell, she was kicked several times on her right side; Reckzin later reported having seen Burdi kick her in the face.\n\nIn 1995, as a result of the violent confrontation, Burdi was convicted of [[assault causing bodily harm]], and sentenced to 12 months imprisonment. Burdi appealed both his conviction and the sentence, but on February 14, 1997, the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] upheld the lower court's 1995 decision ([[s:HMQ vs George Burdi|O.J. No. 554 No. C21788/C21820]]), and Burdi began his sentence. The court \"ruled him out as the kicker,\" but he was found guilty of vicarious liability by having led the charge across the street. Burdi continues to deny having assaulted Reckzin.\n\n=== Renunciation of racism ===\nIn 1997, much of Resistance Record's inventory and business paraphernalia were seized in an April raid by the [[Oakland County, Michigan]] Sheriff's Department, the [[Michigan Department of the Treasury]], and the [[Ontario Provincial Police]]. The same day this raid was carried out in Michigan, Burdi was arrested in [[Windsor, Ontario]], for contravening the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Canadian Criminal Code]] provisions against promoting hatred.\n\nConvicted in Windsor, Burdi was able to avoid a jail sentence with the condition that he not be involved with RaHoWa or Resistance Records. He sold the company to [[Willis Carto]] who soon sold it to [[National Alliance (Canada)|National Alliance]] head [[William Luther Pierce]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Atkins|first=Stephen|title=Encyclopedia of Right-Wing Extremism in Modern American History|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1598843507|page=62}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/resistance_records/introduction.asp Deafening Hate: The Revival of Resistance Records<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620073603/http://adl.org/resistance_records/introduction.asp |date=20 June 2010 }}</ref> Burdi then renounced white nationalism.<ref>{{cite news |title= 'Hatecore' uses music to lure angry white youth |author= Tony Norman |url= http://www.post-gazette.com/columnists/20020219tony0219p3.asp |newspaper= Post-Gazette |date= 19 February 2002 |accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2001-01-25/news.html A racist no longer: Ex-white rights fan just wants to be a rock star] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050111031141/http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2001-01-25/news.html |date=11 January 2005 }} 25 January 2001 article from [[Toronto]]'s ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Magazine]]''.</ref>\n\n=== Return to racism ===\nIn 2017, Burdi revealed that he felt he had never truly abandoned white nationalism and claimed that the media took statements that he made during his hiatus from \"the movement\" out of context. Burdi maintained contact with up to 100 individuals active in right-wing extremist movements, mainly in Europe, throughout the period in which he had allegedly abandoned racism. Burdi further stated that the esoteric neo-Nazi [[Savitri Devi]], who combined [[Nazism]] with [[Hinduism]], sparked his interest in Hinduism and helped him connect with his Hindu wife. Burdi also stated that he views the development of the [[alt-right]] as a positive thing and questions whether he ever would have abandoned [[neo-Nazism]] if he had lived in Europe at the time of his disillusionment with the [[skinhead]] scene.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G2EKphh-Cno]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> In the same year, there appeared a bootleg RaHoWa album with lyrics glorifying [[white supremacy]], calling white people \"the greatest race to ever walk the earth.\"<ref>http://www.lyricsfreak.com/r/rahowa/ode+to+a+dying+people_20772418.html</ref> Burdi has disclaimed currently holding these views.\n\nIn the same interview with the German neo-Nazis, Burdi praises a fascist musical group from France called Les Brigandes and their music video \"Le grand remplacement\", which promotes a conspiracy theory alleging that Jews are in favor of an \"Islamic invasion\" of Europe in order to bring about conditions for the coming of the \"[[Messiah]] of Israel.\"\n\n===Novacosm===\nIn 1998 Burdi founded the multi-racial band Novacosm.<ref name=\"Kinsella2011\">{{cite book|author=Warren Kinsella|title=Fury's Hour: A (sort-of) Punk Manifesto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tAKSNLj1wGEC&pg=PT166|date=27 July 2011|publisher=Random House of Canada|isbn=978-0-307-36972-7|pages=166\u2013}}</ref>  The band, with Burdi on vocals and guitar, B. Valentine on bass and Sy Sylver on guitar, began performing publicly in 2001, and released some recordings as [[MP3|mp3s]]. Novacosm released one [[compact disc]], ''Everything Forever'', in 2003.<ref>[http://ink19.com/2003/08/magazine/music-reviews/novacosm \"Novacosm Everything Forever EP (plus enhanced CD)\"]. ''Inc19'', music review by Troy Jewell. August 6, 2003</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Novacosm recorded a new, acoustic version of \"Ode to a Dying People\", which Burdi had recorded with RaHoWa and released on the band's 1995 album, ''Cult of the Holy War''.\n\n===Uberfolk===\n\nIn 2017, a bootleg album was released called ''Uberfolk''.<ref>https://www.metal-archives.com/albums/Rahowa/Ueberfolk/641099</ref> This album was not authorised by Burdi.\n\nIn 2019, an album called ''Music for Nations'' by a band named Uberfolk was released, with Burdi sharing the vocals with Cat Weiss.<ref>https://uberfolk.bandcamp.com/album/music-for-nations</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.disinfo.com/2012/08/the-disinfocast-with-matt-staggs-former-white-power-activist-george-burdi/ Disinfocast with Matt Staggs \u2013 2012 Audio Interview].\n* [http://www.lifeafterhate.org Life After Hate \u2013 U.S.-based organization].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051218122102/http://www.web.apc.org/~ara/documents/news/appeal.htm Ontario Court of Appeal]\n* [http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=179 Present at the Creation] Interview with Burdi by the anti-racist [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].\n* [http://www.novacosm.com/ Novacosm band website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220194003/http://www.spike.com/video-clips/uakf42/novacosm IFILM about George Burdi and Novacosm]\n* [http://www.acidlogic.com/georgeburdi.htm I am not my DNA] recent interview from ''Acid Logic''.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051222094103/http://www.tolerance.org/news/article_hate.jsp?id=402 Interview With Burdi]\n* [http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/vh1_news_special/56815/episode_videos.jhtml Leaving Racism Behind] Video Interview. George Burdi talks about leaving hate behind.\n{{Hate in Canada}}\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burdi, George}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian neo-Nazis]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Creativity (religion)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = George Burdi\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| alias               = George Eric Hawthorne\n| birth_date          = {{birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place         = Canada\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Goth metal]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1988\u20132007, 2017\u2013present\n| associated_acts     = [[RAHOWA (band)|RaHoWa]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''George Burdi''', also known as '''George Eric Hawthorne''' (born 1970), is a Canadian musician and [[white supremacist]] who became known for his role in [[white nationalist]] organizations. He led the Canadian branch of the [[World Church of the Creator]], which formed an alliance with the now-defunct white nationalist organization [[Heritage Front]]. In addition, Burdi performed with the white power band [[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]].<ref name=\"Dyck2016\">{{cite book|author=Kirsten Dyck|title=Reichsrock: The International Web of White-Power and Neo-Nazi Hate Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sREVDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA113|date=3 October 2016|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-7473-8|pages=113\u2013}}</ref>\n\nBurdi was convicted of [[assault causing bodily harm]], and was sentenced to one year in prison. Upon his release from prison, Burdi claimed to have renounced racism, but years later revealed that he actually was and still is a racist.\n\n== Early life ==\nBurdi was born in 1970 to an Italian immigrant father and a Ukrainian mother.\n\n==Activism==\nBurdi came into contact with the white nationalist movement through the father of his then German girlfriend. He became an active White nationalist at the age of 18, and by the age of 21, was the leader of the Canadian branch of the World Church of the Creator, which at its peak had fewer than 20 members.<ref>[http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=179 SPLCenter.org: Present at the Creation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> During this period, he wrote a number of articles for the Church of the Creator newspaper, ''Racial Loyalty'', using the name \"Rev. Eric Hawthorne\" (including the January 1992 cover story, \"Enter the Racial Holy War\"). He has been credited with helping to secure the survival of [[Creativity (religion)|Creativity]] after the death, in 1993, of its founder [[Ben Klassen]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Michael | first1 = George | title = The Church of the Creator Part I: Ben Klassen and the Critique of Christianity | journal = Religion Compass | volume = 4 | pages = 518 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1111/j.1749-8171.2010.00234.x}}</ref>\n\n=== RaHoWa ===\nUsing the pseudonym \"Reverend George Eric Hawthorne\", Burdi formed the racist band [[RaHoWa (band)|RaHoWa]] in 1989. The band's name was derived from the phrase [[Racial Holy War]].<ref name=\"Dyck2016\" /> RaHoWa was one of the largest hate-rock bands throughout the 1990s.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} Burdi was also the founding president of [[Resistance Records]], which was the distributor for his band, and other white nationalist bands. The company also operated a web site, and published a magazine, ''Resistance'', which covered the white nationalist music scene.\n\nIn 2017, Burdi returned to performing with RaHoWa; [[Appalachian State University]] political science professor Nancy S. Love, author of ''Trendy Fascism'', remarked, during a 2018 interview with ''The Financial Times'', that, after having been \"silent for almost 20 years but in 2017 resurfaced, emboldened by the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump presidency]] and also the turn to the right in Europe\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter-Tilney |first1=Ludovic |title=The re-emergence of white supremacist pop |url=https://www.ft.com/content/68033ace-9732-11e8-b747-fb1e803ee64e |accessdate=9 November 2019 |publisher=The Financial Times Ltd. |date=17 August 2018 |language=EN}}</ref>\n\n=== Reckzin incident ===\nIn [[Ottawa]], on May 29, 1993, after a RaHoWa concert which was picketed by [[Anti-Racist Action]] protesters, Burdi and the leader of the White nationalist Heritage Front, [[Wolfgang Droege]], led their supporters on a march to [[Parliament Hill]], chanting \"[[Nazi salute|sieg heil]]\", making racist remarks, and giving the [[Hitler salute]]. At Parliament Hill, the two addressed their followers.\n\nBurdi then led the group to the Chateau Laurier, where he led a charge across the street to confront protesters. During the charge, Alicia Reckzin  was struck on the head while running from Burdi's supporters. When she fell, she was kicked several times on her right side; Reckzin later reported having seen Burdi kick her in the face.\n\nIn 1995, as a result of the violent confrontation, Burdi was convicted of [[assault causing bodily harm]], and sentenced to 12 months imprisonment. Burdi appealed both his conviction and the sentence, but on February 14, 1997, the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] upheld the lower court's 1995 decision ([[s:HMQ vs George Burdi|O.J. No. 554 No. C21788/C21820]]), and Burdi began his sentence. The court \"ruled him out as the kicker,\" but he was found guilty of vicarious liability by having led the charge across the street. Burdi continues to deny having assaulted Reckzin.\n\n=== Renunciation of racism ===\nIn 1997, much of Resistance Record's inventory and business paraphernalia were seized in an April raid by the [[Oakland County, Michigan]] Sheriff's Department, the [[Michigan Department of the Treasury]], and the [[Ontario Provincial Police]]. The same day this raid was carried out in Michigan, Burdi was arrested in [[Windsor, Ontario]], for contravening the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Canadian Criminal Code]] provisions against promoting hatred.\n\nConvicted in Windsor, Burdi was able to avoid a jail sentence with the condition that he not be involved with RaHoWa or Resistance Records. He sold the company to [[Willis Carto]] who soon sold it to [[National Alliance (Canada)|National Alliance]] head [[William Luther Pierce]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Atkins|first=Stephen|title=Encyclopedia of Right-Wing Extremism in Modern American History|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1598843507|page=62}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/resistance_records/introduction.asp Deafening Hate: The Revival of Resistance Records<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620073603/http://adl.org/resistance_records/introduction.asp |date=20 June 2010 }}</ref> Burdi then renounced white nationalism.<ref>{{cite news |title= 'Hatecore' uses music to lure angry white youth |author= Tony Norman |url= http://www.post-gazette.com/columnists/20020219tony0219p3.asp |newspaper= Post-Gazette |date= 19 February 2002 |accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2001-01-25/news.html A racist no longer: Ex-white rights fan just wants to be a rock star] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050111031141/http://www.nowtoronto.com/issues/2001-01-25/news.html |date=11 January 2005 }} 25 January 2001 article from [[Toronto]]'s ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Magazine]]''.</ref>\n\n=== Return to racism ===\nIn 2017, Burdi revealed that he felt he had never truly abandoned white nationalism and claimed that the media took statements that he made during his hiatus from \"the movement\" out of context. Burdi maintained contact with up to 100 individuals active in right-wing extremist movements, mainly in Europe, throughout the period in which he had allegedly abandoned racism. Burdi further stated that the esoteric neo-Nazi [[Savitri Devi]], who combined [[Nazism]] with [[Hinduism]], sparked his interest in Hinduism and helped him connect with his Hindu wife. Burdi also stated that he views the development of the [[alt-right]] as a positive thing and questions whether he ever would have abandoned [[neo-Nazism]] if he had lived in Europe at the time of his disillusionment with the [[skinhead]] scene.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G2EKphh-Cno</ref> In the same year, there appeared a bootleg RaHoWa album with lyrics glorifying [[white supremacy]], calling white people \"the greatest race to ever walk the earth.\"<ref>http://www.lyricsfreak.com/r/rahowa/ode+to+a+dying+people_20772418.html</ref> Burdi has disclaimed currently holding these views.\n\nIn the same interview with the German neo-Nazis, Burdi praises a fascist musical group from France called Les Brigandes and their music video \"Le grand remplacement\", which promotes a conspiracy theory alleging that Jews are in favor of an \"Islamic invasion\" of Europe in order to bring about conditions for the coming of the \"[[Messiah]] of Israel.\"\n\n===Novacosm===\nIn 1998 Burdi founded the multi-racial band Novacosm.<ref name=\"Kinsella2011\">{{cite book|author=Warren Kinsella|title=Fury's Hour: A (sort-of) Punk Manifesto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tAKSNLj1wGEC&pg=PT166|date=27 July 2011|publisher=Random House of Canada|isbn=978-0-307-36972-7|pages=166\u2013}}</ref>  The band, with Burdi on vocals and guitar, B. Valentine on bass and Sy Sylver on guitar, began performing publicly in 2001, and released some recordings as [[MP3|mp3s]]. Novacosm released one [[compact disc]], ''Everything Forever'', in 2003.<ref>[http://ink19.com/2003/08/magazine/music-reviews/novacosm \"Novacosm Everything Forever EP (plus enhanced CD)\"]. ''Inc19'', music review by Troy Jewell. August 6, 2003</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Novacosm recorded a new, acoustic version of \"Ode to a Dying People\", which Burdi had recorded with RaHoWa and released on the band's 1995 album, ''Cult of the Holy War''.\n\n===Uberfolk===\n\nIn 2017, a bootleg album was released called ''Uberfolk''.<ref>https://www.metal-archives.com/albums/Rahowa/Ueberfolk/641099</ref> This album was not authorised by Burdi.\n\nIn 2019, an album called ''Music for Nations'' by a band named Uberfolk was released, with Burdi sharing the vocals with Cat Weiss.<ref>https://uberfolk.bandcamp.com/album/music-for-nations</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.disinfo.com/2012/08/the-disinfocast-with-matt-staggs-former-white-power-activist-george-burdi/ Disinfocast with Matt Staggs \u2013 2012 Audio Interview].\n* [http://www.lifeafterhate.org Life After Hate \u2013 U.S.-based organization].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051218122102/http://www.web.apc.org/~ara/documents/news/appeal.htm Ontario Court of Appeal]\n* [http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=179 Present at the Creation] Interview with Burdi by the anti-racist [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].\n* [http://www.novacosm.com/ Novacosm band website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220194003/http://www.spike.com/video-clips/uakf42/novacosm IFILM about George Burdi and Novacosm]\n* [http://www.acidlogic.com/georgeburdi.htm I am not my DNA] recent interview from ''Acid Logic''.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051222094103/http://www.tolerance.org/news/article_hate.jsp?id=402 Interview With Burdi]\n* [http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/vh1_news_special/56815/episode_videos.jhtml Leaving Racism Behind] Video Interview. George Burdi talks about leaving hate behind.\n{{Hate in Canada}}\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burdi, George}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian neo-Nazis]]\n[[Category:Canadian people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock singers]]\n[[Category:Creativity (religion)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n", "name_user": "Mikeblas", "label": "safe", "comment": "dead link", "url_page": "//en.